column111: 17+2wks - admitted with PV bleed and bulging membranes, 3cm dilated. Rescued Cerclarge discussed and consented. Into theatre. Sim's Speculum posteriorly: Bulging membranes - no cervix felt - fully dilated. Continuous leak of hind water liquor - increases with pushing the forewater. Rupture of membranes was already obvious from hindwater leak. Trial to reach the cervix with pushing of membranes to be 100% sure it is not exudation. Done anteriorly and posteriorly but noted the water increased - definite hindwater rupture of membranes confirmed. Forewater ruptured during manipulation. Slightly offensive smell of the liquor. Procedure abandoned. Woman counselled and MTOP consented. Toxoplasmosis positive.

column271:
Potters like appearance. More comments from Bedford where delivered: Diagnosis: Respiratory distress syndrome, Pneumothorax, Pulmonary hypoplasia.
During stay:Ventilated for 1 day. Intubated at delivery (13 min), given Curosurf (14 min) and started on PC-AC VG 5mL/kg, FiO2 1.0 ventilation. Ventilation
was very quickly changed to conventional PC-AC using increasing pressures up to 36/6. Significant concerns regarding oxygenation (sats
65%) despite FiO2 1.0. In total 5 Curosurf doses were given (total 1.2g). With each administration sats improved transiently, peak saturations obtain 94%, before once again decreasing.
First gas demonstrated a significant mixed acidosis, with a pH 6.5, pCO2 24, lactate 18.
A right pneumothorax was identified on CXR at 2 hours of age. Chest drain inserted. Air aspirated. CXR demonstrated good position of drain and resolution of pneumothroax, following this however saturations continued to deteriorate to 40% in FiO2 100%.
